  stickyNoteInfos:
  - title: 'Set Color From Curve:'
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: 1375
      y: 2490
      width: 489
      height: 172
    contents: "The \u201Cattribute from curve\u201D allows us to \u201Cset\u201D
      an attribute value with a curve/gradient. This is powerful and gives some nice
      artistic control.\r\n\r\nIn this case, we're able to define a \u201Ccolor ramp\u201D.\r\nFrom
      here, we set the \u201Csampler mode\u201D to random. Each particle will be
      given a random color in the color gradient that we defined.\r\n\r\nThere's
      a different sampling mode so that we can sample the gradient thanks to the
      particle's speed, overlife, etc.\r\n"
    theme: 
    textSize: Small
    colorTheme: 2
  - title: '!! Computed Source Code !!'
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: 1373
      y: 2713
      width: 385
      height: 193
    contents: "A great way to learn or understand what's being done by a \r\n\u201CContext
      Block\u201D is to go to:\n\nPreferences>Visual Effects> and to turn on \u201CShow
      Additional Debug Info.\u201D\n\nBy doing so, when selecting a \u201Ccontext
      block,\u201D you'll be able to see the generated code and attributes that are
      read and written.\r\n"
    theme: 
    textSize: Small
    colorTheme: 3
  - title: 'Init Position:'
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: 396
      y: 696
      width: 286
      height: 165
    contents: 'We''re using a sphere property to spawn our particles on this sphere,
      thanks to a Shape: Sphere block.



      Using a sphere property allows us
      to reuse the sphere information (transforms, radius, etc.) later on in the
      update and output context.

'
    theme: 
    textSize: Small
    colorTheme: 2
  - title: 'Bounds:'
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: 1375
      y: 559
      width: 256
      height: 111
    contents: 'We''re using our sphere property for our bound center and size.

      This
      way, the bounds will match our initial particle''s position on the sphere.

'
    theme: 
    textSize: Small
    colorTheme: 2
  - title: 'Conform to Sphere:'
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: 1373
      y: 1164
      width: 243
      height: 100
    contents: This block allows you to keep particles inside a sphere. You can play
      with the Attraction Force and Stick Force settings.
    theme: 
    textSize: Small
    colorTheme: 2
  - title: 'Turbulence:'
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: 1371
      y: 1385
      width: 243
      height: 138
    contents: "The Turbulence Block allows you to add some randomness to your velocity.
      It's interesting to add more organic motion to your particles.\r\nHere we're
      also using a \u201Ctime\u201D operator to offset the transform of the noise.
      This allows for more intriguing motion.\r\n"
    theme: 
    textSize: Small
    colorTheme: 2
  - title: 'Scale & Size:'
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: 1377
      y: 2209
      width: 417
      height: 269
    contents: 'The scale is the attribute that controls the scale of the particles.
      By default, it''s a vector3.

      The final size of the particles is equal
      to Scale * Size attribute.



      The scale attribute is used when you want
      to have a non-uniform scale for quads or meshes.



      The scale attribute
      allows you to control the size ratio on X/Y/Z. The final size is: scale attribute
      * size attribute.



      Note: The scale attribute is "variadic". This means
      that its type can change based on the channel settings. If you''re not using
      a mesh but only a 2D quad, you can set it to XY. This way, the attribute will
      be a Vector2 instead of a Vector3, and this can help you save some memory.

'
    theme: 
    textSize: Small
    colorTheme: 2
  - title: 'Orient Advanced:'
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: -255
      y: 2489
      width: 554
      height: 212
    contents: "In advanced mode, the orient block needs two vectors to properly orient
      the particles.\r\n\r\nThe Z-axis is the facing vector, while the Y-axis is
      the alignment vector.\r\nHere, we want our particle to always face the sphere
      normals, so: \r\n\r\nSphere Normals = particles. Position - Sphere.center =
      AxisZ\r\n\r\nFor the alignment vector AxisY, we're using the velocity, so that
      they align with their velocity direction.\r\n\r\nNote that we don't need to
      normalize our vectors, as the Orient Block is already doing a normalization
      operation.\r\n"
    theme: 
    textSize: Small
    colorTheme: 3
  - title: Orient Advanced
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: 929
      y: -54
      width: 669
      height: 110
    contents: 
    theme: 
    textSize: Huge
    colorTheme: 2
  - title: 'Output Triangle :'
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: 1380
      y: 1993
      width: 250
      height: 181
    contents: "The output particle has many options for you to experiment with!\r\nYou
      can control the Blend Mode (Opaque, Translucent, Additive), change how the
      UVs are handled, or even the \u201Cprimitive type.\u201D\r\n\r\nIn the Inspector
      tab, after selecting the \u201Coutput context\u201D block, we've changed the
      \u201Cprimitive type\u201D from quad to triangle.\r\n"
    theme: 
    textSize: Small
    colorTheme: 2
  categories: []
  uiBounds:
    serializedVersion: 2
    x: -280
    y: -113
    width: 2169
    height: 3044
